Tiddlers of type `x-twikki` are rendered as markdown by the [[$BaseMarkdownPlugin]].

The flavor is CommonMark implemented by [markdown-it 14.2.0](https://github.com/markdown-it/markdown-it) but can be overriden by creating a plugin.

## Custom Renderers
A custom plugin can implement a `render()` function to override the `markdown.render` functionality:
```javascript
function myRenderer(markdown) {
  // Implement your renderer here..
  return MyRenderer.toHtml(text); // must return an HTML string
}
tw.core.markdown = {render: myRenderer};
tw.events.override('markdown.render', myRenderer);
```

If no handler is subscribed (e.g. `?safemode`), the platform falls back to escaped plain text.

## Plugins

In TWikki there is no special "plugin" format — **a plugin is just a tiddler**. Because *code is data*, any tiddler of type `script/js` is executable, so **installing a plugin means adding a tiddler** and uninstalling means deleting it.

See [[Concepts]] for how tiddler types work, and [[Packages]] for how plugins are shared.

## How code tiddlers run

* A `script/js` tiddler is executed with `eval()` in the **global context**:
  * once when TWikki starts, and
  * again whenever you edit and save it, so changes take effect immediately
* Code tiddlers are run as part of validation on save — if the code throws, the save reports the error
* Tag a code tiddler with `$CodeDisabled` to stop it from executing

## The basic shape

A plugin is usually an immediately-invoked function that hooks into the global `tw` namespace:

```js
(function() {
  tw.events.subscribe('ui.loaded', () => {
    tw.ui.notify('Hello from my plugin!', 'D');
  }, 'MyPlugin');
})();
```

See [[TW API]] for more details

## Macros

A macro is a speciall command inside `<<...>>` blocks in markdown which runs and produces dynamic content and/or UI elements (like buttons). A macro returns a string of markdown/HTML that is rendered in place.

For example `<<include $TWikkiVersion>>` will include the `$TWikkiVersion` tiddler's content and produce:
> <<include $TWikkiVersion>>

## User Macros
Core or base macros reside in the global namespace. When you install a plugin it should have a namespace so that macros don't collide.

```js
tw.extensions.registerMacro('greet', 'hello', (name) => {
  return `Hello ${name}!`;
}, {version: '1.0.0'});
```

This registers a macro so it can be used as `<<greet.hello "Marc">>` anywhere. 

See [[ExamplePlugin]] for a fuller worked example, and [[$GeneralWidgets]] for the built-in widgets.

## Reacting to events

Subscribe to lifecycle events to extend behaviour. Some useful ones:

* `ui.loaded` — the UI has finished its first render
* `tiddler.rendered` — a tiddler was (re)rendered; the handler receives its element
* `tiddler.updated` / `tiddler.deleted` — the store changed
* `script.loaded` — an external script you added has finished loading
* `theme.switch` — the active theme changed

```js
tw.events.subscribe('tiddler.rendered', ({tiddler, newElement}) => {
  // decorate freshly-rendered tiddlers here
}, 'MyPlugin.HandleRenderedTiddler');
```

Always pass a unique **name** of your handler as the third argument so your handler is identifiable and is not registered twice when the tiddler re-runs.

## Replacing the markdown renderer

Markdown rendering is itself a plugin. The platform renders tiddlers by sending the `markdown.render` event and using the first handler's result; [[$BaseMarkdownPlugin]] subscribes the bundled markdown-it implementation. To swap in your own implementation or flavor, override the handler from any code tiddler:

```js
tw.events.override('markdown.render', function myMarkdown(text) {
  return MyRenderer.toHtml(text); // must return an HTML string
});
```

Your package's code runs after the base package, so the override wins on every boot and reload. At runtime, follow it with `tw.events.send('ui.reload')` to re-render. If **no** handler is subscribed (e.g. in `?safemode`), TWikki falls back to rendering tiddlers as escaped plain text.

The default markdown-it instance is exposed as `tw.core.markdown.md`, so you can also *extend* rather than replace it (e.g. `tw.core.markdown.md.use(...)` — see [[$OpenLinksInNewWindow]]).

## Loading external libraries

Need a third-party library or stylesheet? Load it from a CDN and react when it is ready:

```js
tw.events.subscribe('ui.loaded', () => {
  tw.core.dom.addScript('my-lib', 'https://cdn.example.com/lib.min.js');
  tw.events.subscribe('script.loaded', (name) => {
    if (name === 'my-lib') tw.lib.myLib = window.MyLib;
  }, 'MyPlugin');
}, 'MyPlugin');
```

This is exactly how the built-in syntax-highlighting plugin pulls in Highlight.js.

## Distributing plugins

A plugin is shared like any other tiddler — inside a package (a JSON list of tiddlers). Packages are loaded from the URLs listed in [[$CorePackages]] and [[$ExtensionPackages]], or imported on demand with the `<<packages.import>>` widget. A whole plugin can even live in a single multi-section tiddler — see [[ExamplePlugin]].
